237
00:13:38,520 --> 00:13:40,795
[COMPUTER CHIMES]

238
00:13:40,959 --> 00:13:42,233
It's him.

239
00:13:42,439 --> 00:13:44,077
He's trying to video chat.

240
00:13:48,159 --> 00:13:50,957
Perhaps I shouldn't have taken this
into the real world.

241
00:13:51,600 --> 00:13:53,033
Oh, really?

242
00:13:56,040 --> 00:13:58,508
"'Time travel, I don't understand,'
said Amelia.

243
00:13:58,720 --> 00:14:01,188
Cooper stared at her,
'Which word don't you understand...

244
00:14:01,400 --> 00:14:03,277
...time or travel?"'

245
00:14:03,759 --> 00:14:07,638
Wow, even in your fantasies
Sheldon's kind of exhausting.

246
00:14:08,719 --> 00:14:11,438
He's like that in the beginning
so she can change him.

247
00:14:11,639 --> 00:14:12,913
It's called good writing.

248
00:14:14,160 --> 00:14:15,957
And wishful thinking.

249
00:14:17,040 --> 00:14:19,110
"It stung Amelia
when he spoke to her this way.

250
00:14:19,319 --> 00:14:22,277
In her one-room schoolhouse
she was always the smartest student...

251
00:14:22,480 --> 00:14:25,916
...regularly besting the boys in her class.
But this was no boy in front of her.

252
00:14:26,120 --> 00:14:27,109
This was a man."

253
00:14:27,319 --> 00:14:28,957
Here we go.

254
00:14:29,160 --> 00:14:32,550
"Cooper told Amelia about all the
incredible things the future would hold...

255
00:14:32,759 --> 00:14:35,432
...like computers and living past 30.

256
00:14:35,639 --> 00:14:37,357
He asked her if she had any questions.

257
00:14:37,560 --> 00:14:40,711
All she longed to ask was if his heart
was beating as fast as hers...

258
00:14:40,920 --> 00:14:43,150
...but she was too afraid
to hear the answer."

259
00:14:43,360 --> 00:14:44,588
Oh, Amelia.

260
00:14:44,800 --> 00:14:49,078
"So instead she asked if in the future
Montana ever became a state."

261
00:14:52,879 --> 00:14:55,996
Hey, in the 1800s,
that was considered flirting.

262
00:14:57,960 --> 00:15:00,918
I'm so sick of people
being mean on the Internet.

263
00:15:01,120 --> 00:15:04,396
I think the anonymity makes everyone
feel like they can say things...

264
00:15:04,600 --> 00:15:06,113
...they'd never say to your face.

265
00:15:07,040 --> 00:15:08,473
Interesting.

266
00:15:08,680 --> 00:15:12,434
I can't think of a single thing
I wouldn't say to someone's face.

267
00:15:13,800 --> 00:15:15,597
I never noticed that about you.

268
00:15:17,199 --> 00:15:20,316
You know what,
at least you guys did something.

269
00:15:20,519 --> 00:15:25,229
You know, you had a theory, you wrote
a paper, you made an actual contribution.

270
00:15:25,439 --> 00:15:28,590
All guys like this do is just tear down
other people's work.

271
00:15:29,919 --> 00:15:31,352
He's right.

272
00:15:32,199 --> 00:15:35,271
You know, I say we call this person back.

273
00:15:35,480 --> 00:15:37,675
We've got no reason to hide.

274
00:15:39,240 --> 00:15:41,071
All right, do it. Call him.

275
00:15:41,280 --> 00:15:44,113
Let's find out what this loser's
ever accomplished.

276
00:15:47,160 --> 00:15:48,752
Click it with me.

277
00:15:50,079 --> 00:15:52,798
-One, two, three, click.
-Click.

278
00:15:52,959 --> 00:15:54,711
[COMPUTER DIALING]

279
00:15:55,279 --> 00:15:57,395
HAWKING [OVER COMPUTER]:
Well, hello, there.

280
00:15:58,320 --> 00:15:59,912
Professor Hawking?

281
00:16:00,120 --> 00:16:03,430
Oh, brother, you should see
the look on your faces.

282
00:16:05,639 --> 00:16:07,675
You really didn't like our paper?

283
00:16:07,879 --> 00:16:10,154
I like your paper very much.

284
00:16:10,360 --> 00:16:12,476
The premise is intriguing.

285
00:16:13,040 --> 00:16:14,996
Then why are you attacking us?

286
00:16:15,200 --> 00:16:20,149
If you were sitting in a chair for 40 years,
you'd get bored too.

287
00:16:22,480 --> 00:16:24,232
Anyway, gotta go.

288
00:16:24,439 --> 00:16:28,318
I promised to help the neighbor kid
with his math homework.

289
00:16:29,840 --> 00:16:30,955
Ciao.

290
00:16:34,360 --> 00:16:36,590
Stephen Hawking liked our paper. Heh.

291
00:16:37,840 --> 00:16:40,559
He said the premise is intriguing.

292
00:16:41,079 --> 00:16:45,277
Good to see you again,
Mr. Stephen-Hawking-Liked-Our-Paper.

293
00:16:46,959 --> 00:16:50,315
And you as well,
Mr. Our-Premise-ls-lntriguing.

294
00:16:51,160 --> 00:16:54,709
How do you do,
Mr. I'll-Admit-That's-Pretty-Cool?

295
00:16:55,959 --> 00:16:58,473
Yeah, you keep setting me up for failure.

296
00:17:01,319 --> 00:17:04,550
"With a heavy heart, Amelia stood
before the newly-repaired time machine.

297
00:17:04,760 --> 00:17:07,228
She regretted giving Cooper
the part he needed."

298
00:17:07,439 --> 00:17:10,351
Because she wanted him
to give her the part she needed.

299
00:17:12,400 --> 00:17:15,949
-Okay, that's enough.
-No, I really wanna know what happens.

300
00:17:16,160 --> 00:17:18,879
And Bernadette really, really,
wants to know what happens.

301
00:17:20,839 --> 00:17:22,238
You're just making fun of me.

302
00:17:22,439 --> 00:17:25,237
No, l was just kidding, I'm sorry.
And the story's really good.

303
00:17:25,439 --> 00:17:27,157
No, it is. Does he stay?

304
00:17:27,360 --> 00:17:30,796
Do they kiss?
Does she find out about Montana?

305
00:17:32,039 --> 00:17:33,472
Please?

306
00:17:33,759 --> 00:17:35,112
Fine.

307
00:17:36,799 --> 00:17:41,589
"As Cooper prepared to depart,
tears filled Amelia's eyes.

308
00:17:41,799 --> 00:17:46,668
He took her hand in his and said,
'I can't stay, but I will never forget you.'

309
00:17:47,480 --> 00:17:52,235
He brushed his fingers against her cheek,
then quickly stepped into the machine.

310
00:17:52,439 --> 00:17:56,114
'Please don't go,' she whispered,
but it was too late.

311
00:17:56,319 --> 00:17:58,071
The engine hummed to life."

312
00:17:58,279 --> 00:18:00,190
But they didn't even kiss.

313
00:18:00,919 --> 00:18:04,798
"She turned away, wiping her eyes.
She couldn't bear to watch...

314
00:18:04,999 --> 00:18:07,991
...her one chance at true love
disappear forever.

315
00:18:08,199 --> 00:18:12,477
Then she felt a strong hand
on her shoulder spin her around.

316
00:18:12,720 --> 00:18:13,709
It was Cooper."

317
00:18:13,959 --> 00:18:14,914
[INHALES]

318
00:18:15,079 --> 00:18:16,068
Yes.

319
00:18:18,159 --> 00:18:20,593
"'What about the future?' asked Amelia.

320
00:18:20,799 --> 00:18:23,393
He looked deeply into her eyes
and whispered:

321
00:18:23,599 --> 00:18:25,715
'There is no future without you.'

322
00:18:26,480 --> 00:18:27,993
He pulled her in close.

323
00:18:28,520 --> 00:18:30,636
She began to tremble all over.

324
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:32,913
She felt his warm breath--"

325
00:18:33,120 --> 00:18:36,157
-You won't believe what Stephen Hawking--
-Get out!

326
00:18:46,999 --> 00:18:49,194
Is the water warm enough?

327
00:18:49,679 --> 00:18:53,035
Given the fact that you took the time
to build a wood fire...

328
00:18:53,240 --> 00:18:56,949
...draw the water from the well and heat it,
it would be rude to complain.

329
00:18:59,240 --> 00:19:01,708
But since you asked, it's a little nippy.

330
00:19:02,920 --> 00:19:04,592
I can fix that.

331
00:19:09,640 --> 00:19:13,872
I couldn't help but notice
your unusual undergarments.

332
00:19:14,080 --> 00:19:17,356
They're not undergarments.
They're Underoos.

333
00:19:19,640 --> 00:19:23,553
Where I come from, they're known
as "Underwear that's fun to wear."

334
00:19:25,359 --> 00:19:28,157
And what's the significance of the spider?

335
00:19:28,360 --> 00:19:30,954
Oh, that represents Spider-Man.

336
00:19:31,160 --> 00:19:33,628
He does whatever a spider can.

337
00:19:36,160 --> 00:19:38,720
There's a lot of rhyming in the future,
isn't there?

338
00:19:39,360 --> 00:19:42,557
You're right.
This is even weirder than I thought.

339
00:19:43,400 --> 00:19:45,994
-You want me to stop reading?
-Are you kidding? No, no.

340
00:19:47,799 --> 00:19:50,836
"As he stood for Amelia to dry him...."

341
00:19:55,359 --> 00:19:57,270
So tell me, Cooper...

342
00:19:57,839 --> 00:20:01,832
...are the ways of physical love
different in the future?

343
00:20:02,039 --> 00:20:03,358
Yeah, okay, I'm good.

344
00:20:30,879 --> 00:20:32,870
[English - us - an]

